        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(qa): crabline channel driver",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- Wires profile-selected `channelDriver: crabline` into QA suite execution instead of only writing Crabline metadata artifacts.\n- Adds a Crabline-backed Telegram QA transport that sends scenario inbound text through Crabline, configures a real OpenClaw Telegram gateway account for SUT replies, and mirrors observed replies back into the existing QA Lab bus.\n- Reuses the existing QA credential lease path so Crabline Telegram can read direct `OPENCLAW_QA_TELEGRAM_*` env locally or lease Telegram credentials from Convex in CI with `OPENCLAW_QA_CREDENTIAL_SOURCE=convex`.\n- Adds `qa run --qa-profile ... --scenario ...` filtering so CI can run a small taxonomy/profile-owned smoke slice while still using the profile's `channelDriver`.\n- Adds a secret-bearing workflow lane that runs the `smoke-ci` profile through Crabline with Convex credential leases.\n- Pins QA Lab's dev-only Crabline dependency to merged `openclaw/crabline@ee1189ad966e9e8d7eea9e38b3ca5965ff48d93c` and lazy-loads it so production OpenClaw dist does not bundle Crabline provider code.\n\n## Linked context\n\n- Uses merged openclaw/crabline#9, which exports the runtime registry/provider API from Crabline's package root.\n- Builds on the earlier profile/taxonomy work in this PR: `smoke-ci` selects `crabline`, `release` declares `live`, and default profiles continue to use `qa-channel`.\n- Related follow-up openclaw/openclaw#91506 preserves suite selections across the isolated runner wrapper.\n\n## CI credential setup\n\n- CI does not need raw `OPENCLAW_QA_TELEGRAM_GROUP_ID`, `OPENCLAW_QA_TELEGRAM_DRIVER_BOT_TOKEN`, or `OPENCLAW_QA_TELEGRAM_SUT_BOT_TOKEN` secrets for this lane.\n- The new `run_smoke_ci_crabline` job in `qa-live-transports-convex.yml` uses the existing `qa-live-shared` secrets: `OPENCLAW_QA_CONVEX_SITE_URL` and `OPENCLAW_QA_CONVEX_SECRET_CI`.\n- The job sets `OPENCLAW_QA_CREDENTIAL_SOURCE=convex` and `OPENCLAW_QA_CREDENTIAL_ROLE=ci`, then runs `pnpm openclaw qa run --qa-profile smoke-ci --category channel-framework.conversation-routing-and-delivery --scenario dm-chat-baseline --provider-mode mock-openai --fast`.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- `pnpm vitest run extensions/qa-lab/src/crabline-transport.test.ts extensions/qa-lab/src/cli.test.ts extensions/qa-lab/src/cli.runtime.test.ts` passes 141/141 tests, including coverage for importing the installed Crabline package and acquiring Telegram credentials through the Convex broker path.\n- `pnpm openclaw qa run --qa-profile smoke-ci --category channel-framework.conversation-routing-and-delivery --scenario dm-chat-baseline --output-dir .artifacts/qa-e2e/crabline-no-env-check --provider-mode mock-openai --fast` resolves `smoke-ci` to one scenario and fails locally at the direct-env fallback with `OPENCLAW_QA_TELEGRAM_DRIVER_BOT_TOKEN is required for --channel-driver crabline telegram.` That proves the taxonomy profile enters Crabline; CI satisfies this with the Convex credential source.\n- A full live Telegram smoke run was not possible in this shell because the Telegram credentials are intentionally brokered through CI secrets.\n\n## Validation\n\n- `pnpm exec tsc -p extensions/qa-lab/tsconfig.json --noEmit`\n- `node scripts/run-oxlint.mjs --tsconfig config/tsconfig/oxlint.extensions.json extensions/qa-lab/src/crabline-transport.ts extensions/qa-lab/src/crabline-transport.test.ts extensions/qa-lab/src/cli.ts extensions/qa-lab/src/cli.test.ts extensions/qa-lab/src/cli.runtime.ts extensions/qa-lab/src/cli.runtime.test.ts`\n- `pnpm vitest run extensions/qa-lab/src/crabline-transport.test.ts extensions/qa-lab/src/cli.test.ts extensions/qa-lab/src/cli.runtime.test.ts`\n- `pnpm openclaw qa run --qa-profile smoke-ci --category channel-framework.conversation-routing-and-delivery --scenario dm-chat-baseline --output-dir .artifacts/qa-e2e/crabline-no-env-check --provider-mode mock-openai --fast` expectedly fails locally at missing direct Telegram QA env.\n- `git diff --check`\n\n## Production bundle/dependency check\n\n- `crabline` appears only in `extensions/qa-lab` `devDependencies`, not `dependencies` or `peerDependencies`.\n- Previous clean build verification on this branch showed `rg \"node_modules/crabline|providers/builtin\" dist -n` returns no matches.\n- Built `dist` still contains expected QA strings like `channel-driver crabline`, but not Crabline provider/runtime chunks.\n\n## Current limits\n\n- QA Lab's Crabline execution transport currently supports Telegram only. Non-Telegram Crabline selections fail explicitly.\n- Generic message actions like reaction/edit/delete are not implemented through the Crabline Telegram transport yet.\n- Telegram direct QA conversations are represented through the configured Telegram QA group because Telegram bots cannot DM each other.\n",
